PREFACE.

THE issue oi this volume to the members oi the Henry Bradshaw Society brings toan end a work which has long been in progress‚ and which had been shared by various hands before it was committed to my own. The early history oi the book is as follows The task of transcribing the Missal oi ⁴ Robert os Jumieges was begun about thirty years ago by the Rev. Francis Procter, now Vice-President os the Society. Mr. Procter, however, did not complete the work, and his unfinished copy was given, some years later, to the Rev. S. S. Lewis, with aview to its completion and publication. The task of tran·

scription was resumed, on Mr. Lewis’ behalf, by a copyist working under the guidance of the late Abbe Sauvage. The work was still unfinished at the time oi Mr. Lewis’ decease,

when the transcript was committed to the Council of the Henry Bradshaw Society, and the task os editing entrusted by the Council to myself.

My own share in the work has been the revision of the copy made by Mr. Procter and by the copyist employed sor Mr. Lewis‚ the transcription oi some portions which still remained uncopied, the preparation of the Introduction and Indices, and the task oi seeing the book through the press. For assistance in this work l have to express my gratitude in the first place to the authorities os the Library of Rouen, who allowed the Missal to be deposited for my use at the Bodleian Library sor such time as was needed sor the completion and revision of the transcript.
